hints_latex:
Note that

\begin{align*}
\frac{d^2}{dx^2}  \sin(\omega x) = -\omega^2\sin(\omega x)
\end{align*}

and that

\begin{align*}
\frac{d^2}{dx^2} \cos(\omega x) = -\omega^2\cos(\omega x)
\end{align*}

sols_latex:
We can rewrite the differential equation as

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle y'' = -4y = -2^2 \cdot y
\end{align*}

Since

\begin{align*}
\frac{d^2}{dx^2} \sin(\omega x) = -\omega^2\sin(x)
\end{align*}

and

\begin{align*}
\frac{d^2}{dx^2} \cos(\omega x) = -\omega^2\cos(x)
\end{align*}

we see that $\displaystyle \sin(\omega x)$ and
$\displaystyle \cos(\omega x)$ are solutions to the equation, with
$\displaystyle \omega = 2$. The solution of the equation must also
satisfy the initial condition $\displaystyle y(0)=1$, which is only the
case for $\displaystyle y = \cos(2x)$. Hence the solution is
$\displaystyle {\color{blue} y =\cos(2x)}$.
